To turn this mock-up into a colorful website, you can use HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. Here's a basic outline of the steps:

1. Create a new HTML file and structure the page with a `<body>` element containing a `<div>` element for the joke container.
2. Inside the `<div>` element, create a `<p>` element for each joke.
3. Use CSS to style the joke container and individual jokes, such as font, color, and background.
4. Add JavaScript to dynamically load the two real jokes into the `<p>` elements.

Here's a simple example of the HTML structure:
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>My Joke Website</title>
    <style>
        .joke-container {
            font-size: 24px;
            background-color: #f2f2f2;
            padding: 20px;
            border-radius: 5px;
        }

        .joke {
            font-size: 18px;
            color: #333;
            background-color: #fff;
            border-radius: 5px;
            padding: 10px;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="joke-container">
        <p class="joke">Isaac, butt joke 2</p>
        <p class="joke">Epithet to moral punchline</p>
    </div>
</body>
</html>
```
For the JavaScript, you can use the `fetch` API to load the two real jokes from a server or a local file. Then, replace the `<p>` elements with the fetched jokes.

Keep in mind that this is just a basic outline, and you may need to adjust the code to fit your specific requirements and preferences.

To create a colorful and interactive website with a real joke replacing the placeholder joke, you can use HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. Here's a basic outline of the structure:

1. Create a container for the joke and the button to reveal the joke.
```html
<div class="joke-container">
  <button class="reveal-button">Reveal Joke</button>
  <p class="joke">Placeholder joke goes here</p>
</div>
```
1. Add a JavaScript function to handle the button click event.
```javascript
const revealButton = document.querySelector('.reveal-button');
revealButton.addEventListener('click', revealJoke);

function revealJoke() {
  const joke = document.querySelector('.joke');
  joke.textContent = 'Real joke goes here';
}
```
1. Style the container and button using CSS.
```css
.joke-container {
  background-color: #f0f0f0;
  border: 1px solid #000;
  padding: 10px;
  margin: 10px;
}

.reveal-button {
  background-color: #000;
  border: 1px solid #000;
  color: #fff;
  padding: 10px;
  margin: 10px;
  cursor: pointer;
}

.reveal-button:hover {
  background-color: #333;
}
```
This is just a basic outline, and you can further enhance the design and functionality of the website by adding more features and styles.
